Name: n-Tridecane
Description: Tridecane is a straight chain alkane containing 13 carbon atoms. It forms a component of the essential oils isolated from plants such as Abelmoschus esculentus. It has a role as a plant metabolite and a volatile oil component.

animal_concentrations.References: (1) Carril Gonzalez-Barros ST et al; Chemosphere 36: 597-602 (1998) (2) Taylor DL et al; Marine Poll Bull 20: 465-68 (1989)
animal_concentrations.Value: The concentration of n-tridecane in tissue samples collected from 12 wolves /Canis lupus signatus/ of Northern Spain was determined to be 7.50 mg/kg lipid weight in suprarenal capsule(1). The concentration of n-tridecane in blubber collected from walruses (Odobenus rosmarus divergens) in six locations of the Pacific Ocean was determined to range from 0 to 0.02 ppm wet weight(2).

fish_seafood_concentrations.Value: Thirteen species of fish collected from the Arabian Gulf during 1985 were found to contain n-tridecane concentrations in muscle ranging from 0.1 (Tylosurus strongylurus) to 0.8 (Acanthopagrus latus) ug/g dry weight(1). n-Tridecane was found in samples of adult lake trout (Salvelinus namaycush) and walleye (Stizostedion v. vitreum) collected in 1977 from Lake Michigan, quantity unknown(2). The concentration of n-tridecane identified in the fish species Boops boops, Scomber japonicus, and Sardina pilchardus collected near the Canary Islands was determined to be 858, 370, and 179 ng/g wet weight, respectively(3). The mean concentration of n-tridecane in channel catfish, bowfin, white catfish, fiddler crab, and sea catfish collected from the Savannah River, Georgia/South Carolina between February 1984 and August 1985 was determined to range from 0.00 to 0.02 ug/g wet weight(4).

sediment_soil_concentrations.References: (1) Akiyama T et al; J UOEH 2: 285-300 (1980) (2) MacLeod WD Jr et al; Symp Fate Effects Petroleum Hydrocarbons on Marine Ecosystems and Organisms pp. 385-96 (1977) (3) Hori T et al; Bull Environ Contam Toxicol 83: 455-61 (2009) (4) Kawata K et al; Bull Environ Contam 65: 660-67 (2000)
sediment_soil_concentrations.Value: SEDIMENT/SOIL: In the heavily industrialized area of Kitakyushu, Japan, n-tridecane was detected but not quantified in sediment(1). n-Tridecane was identified in sediment from Port Angeles Harbor, WA, an area contaminated with fuel oil and in Dungeness Bay, a nearby relatively pristine area, concentration unspecified(2). Surface sediments collected from the Shinano River in Niigata, Japan between November 2005 and April 2006 contained n-tridecane concentrations of <0.1 to 52 ng/g dry weight(3). n-Tridecane was qualitatively detected in sediments collected from Niigata, Japan in September 1995(4).

sediment_soil_concentrations.References: (1) Tassi F et al; Sci Total Environ 407: 4513-25 (2009)
sediment_soil_concentrations.Value: SOIL: n-Tridecane was detected in cover soil at a landfill near Florence, Italy at levels of <2 to 1240 ppbv(1).
